                                                                        	<p><img src="../blog/wp-content/uploads/2007/06/blog-header-2.jpg" border="0" width="635" height="229" /></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><font size="2"><u><strong>Our most precious and fundamental liberties are in danger. </strong></u><br /><br />The Founding Fathers believed the right to one&rsquo;s property was an &ldquo;inherent right&rdquo; endowed by God, and enshrined that right in the Fifth Amendment of the Constitution.   <br /><br />Unfortunately, activist judges and government bureaucrats have eroded this fundamental right over time.  In the Kelo v. New London decision, the Supreme Court rewrote the Constitution to allow government to seize your property and hand it over to private developers. <br /><br />Jim Gilmore believes it is past time for the federal government to become a protector &ndash; not a violator &ndash; of Americans&rsquo; precious liberties. </font></p><p><u><font size="2"><strong>Jim Gilmore&rsquo;s National Property Rights Initiative</strong> </font></u></p><p><font size="2">Property rights will be a major priority in Jim Gilmore&rsquo;s administration.  As President, he will: <br /></font></p><blockquote><ul><li><font size="2">Nominate judges who will strictly interpret the Constitution, rather than making policy from the bench.</font></li><li><font size="2">Appoint a Special Assistant within the White House who will advise the President and oversee the Commission&rsquo;s recommendations.</font></li><li><font size="2">Reissue President Reagan&rsquo;s Executive Order 12630, which directs federal agencies to &ldquo;first do no harm&rdquo; to property rights when writing regulations.</font></li><li><font size="2">Require the Secretary of Housing and Urban Development and other affected cabinet members to issue regular reports to the President on the state of property rights in America.</font></li><li><font size="2">Name a Presidential Commission on Property Rights, which will evaluate the state of property rights in America and craft policy recommendations to the President and Congress that will strengthen protections for property owners.</font></li></ul></blockquote><br /><br /><a href="../mg/files/Property%20Rights%20Handout.pdf"><img src="../mg/files/propertyrightshandout.jpg" border="0" width="153" height="195" /><br />Download a PDF Flier On Jim Gilmore's National Property Rights Initiative</a>
                                                                        
